May 30, 2018

Supervised learning

  • Regression problem: when response \(Y\) is quantitative
    • linear
    • polynomial
  • Decision Tree
  • Random Forest
  • Classification problem: when response \(Y\) is qualitative
    • KNN
    • Trees
    • logistic regression
    • LDA
    • SVM

Linear Model

  • We have input vector \(X^T = \{X_1, X_2,..., X_p\}\) to predict output \(Y\)
    • some of the input variables could be derived from existing variables
    • when some transformation is used, it may create a polynomial regression
  • Model: \(f(X)= \beta_0 + \sum X_j\beta_j\)
  • Least square solution: \(\hat \beta = (X^TX)^{-1}X^Ty\)
  • Predicted value: \(\hat y = X\hat \beta = X(X^TX)^{-1}X^Ty\)
    • Matrix \(H= X(X^TX)^{-1}X^T\) is called the hat matrix or projection matrix
  • \(Var(\hat \beta) = (X^TX)^{-1}\hat \sigma^2\)
    • if two covariates \(X_j\) and \(X_k\) are correlated, the variance will blow up

Variable Selection

  • Least square estimates have low bias but large variance
    • Prediction accuracy can sometimes be improved by shrinking or setting some coefficients to zero
    • less covariates is good for interpretability
  • Subset Selection
    • allows to explore which subset of the covariates are to use
    • requires all possible subsets to be examined
  • Forward and Backward-Stepwise Selection
    • preferred for computational feasibility when \(p\) is large
    • may produce bias
  • Forward-Stagewise Regression: first just fit model \(\bar y\). Start with covariate having largest correlation with residuals and proceed.

Shrinkage Methods

  • Ridge Regression: penalize for larger coefficient (\(\beta\))
    • \(\hat \beta =\underset{\beta} argmin \{(y-\beta_0 - \sum X_j \beta_j)^2 + \lambda\sum \beta_j^2\}\)
  • The Lasso: It is similar to Ridge but penalty is given by \(\sum |\beta_j| <t\)
    • \(\hat \beta =\underset{\beta} argmin \{(y-\beta_0 - \sum X_j \beta_j)^2 + \lambda\sum |\beta_j|\}\)
    • tuning parameter \(t\) can be obtained by \(k\)-fold cross-validation. if \(t > \sum |\hat \beta_j|\), Lasso will produce Least Square estimates. Shrinkage factor \(s = t/\sum |\hat \beta_j|\)
  • Least Angle Regression: forward selection, but add multiple variables in a step
  • Methods Using Derived Input Directions
    • Principal Components(PC) Regression: Obtain \(M\) PC and fit regression
    • Partial Least Squares: Similar to PC but uses \(y\) in addition to \(X\)

Linear models with categorical response

  • Linear regression with categorical response (with K categories)
    • create \(k\) indicator variables \(Y = (Y_1, Y_2, ..., Y_k)\)
    • \(\hat Y = X(X^TX)^{-1}X^Ty\)
  • Logistic regression: response \(Y\) has \(K\) categories with odds ratio \(OR_k = \frac {Pr(Y=k|X)}{Pr(Y=K|X)}\)
    • fit \(K-1\) models \(log(OR_k) = \beta_{k0} + \beta_k^T X\)
    • \(Pr(Y=k|X) = \frac{e^{\beta_{k0} + \beta_k^T X}}{1+ \sum e^{\beta_{k0} + \beta_k^T X}} , k=1,2,..., K-1\)
  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)
    • assumes multivariate normal with equal covariance matrix for all categories
    • boundaries of different class is linear

LDA process

  • Linear discriminant function \(\delta_k(x) = x^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k - \frac 1 2 \mu_k^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k + log (\pi_k)\)
  • decision rule: maximize \(\delta_k(x)\) for class k

non-linear models

  • What if function \(f(X)\) is not linear?
    • \(f(X) = \sum \beta_m h_m(X)\)
  • \(h_m(X) =X\) gives linear model
  • \(h_m(X) =X^p\) gives polynomial
  • \(h_m(X) =log(X) or \sqrt X\) and other nonlinear transformation
  • \(h_m(X) = I(L_m <X_k<U_m)\) gives piecewise non-overlapping regions
    • piecewise polynomial and spline
    • KNN
  • Kernel smoothing methods

Piecewise Linear

Piecewise Cubic Polynomial

Generalized Additive Models (GAM)

  • \(g[\mu(X)] = \alpha + f_1(X_1) + f_2(X_2) + ... + f_p(X_p)\)
    • \(g[\mu] = \mu\) and \(f_j(X_j)=\beta_jX_j\) gives linear regression
    • \(g[\mu] = logit(\mu)\) and \(f_j(X_j)=\beta_jX_j\) gives logistic regression
  • Usually the functions \(f_j()\) are estimated using spline
    • this takes care of non-linearity issues

Fitting Generalized Additive Models in R

library(gam)
library(ISLR) # to get data for our text book
fit <- gam(wage ~ s(age) + s(year) + education, data = Wage)
# summary(fit)
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(fit, se=TRUE)

Tree based method

  • Tree types
    • regression: quantitative \(Y\)
      • \(f(X) = \sum c_m I(x \in R_m)\)
      • \(c_m = avg(y_i|x_i \in R_m)\)
      • classify using split point
    • classification: qualitative \(Y\)
      • \(P_{mk}= \frac 1{N_m}\sum_{x_i \in R_m}I(y_i=k)\)
      • classify observation in node \(m\) to class \(k\) such that \(k(m)=argmax_k P_{mk}\)
  • First partition the input space and then fit model such as mean for each partition.

Improving Prediction

  • A week classifier: slightly better than random guessing
    • The predictions from many weak classifiers are combined to produce the final prediction with less variability
  • Bagging (bootstrap aggregation)
    • resamples training data and aggregate results
  • Random forest
    • Similar to bagging but with a tweak that decorrelates the trees
  • Boosting
    • not based on bootstrapping. Each tree is fit to a modified version of previous data set
    • successive trees are obtained based on previous tree

Neural Network

  • Two stage method for
    • regression: quantitative \(Y\)
    • classification: qualitative \(Y\)
  • hidden layer
    • \(Z_m = \sigma(\alpha_{0m}+ \alpha_m^TX)\)
  • Activation function
    • \(\sigma(v) = 1/(1+e^{-v})\)
    • called sigmoid function
  • \(f_k(X) = g_k(\beta_{0k} + \beta_k^TZ)\)
    • \(g_k(T) = \frac {e^{T_k}}{\sum e^{T_k}}\)

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

  • Supervise learning that can be used for
    • regression
    • classification
  • The algorithm finds a hyperplane that best separates the response categories
    • gamma: larger value tries to fit exact kernel (may over fit)
    • cost: penalty for errors. larger value will compromise the smoothness of hyperplane
    • kernel: smoothing method for hyperplane

Fitting SVM Using R

set.seed (1)
x  <- matrix(rnorm(20*2), ncol=2)
y <- c(rep(-1,10), rep(1,10))
x[y==1,] <- x[y==1,] + 1
plot(x, col=(3-y))

Fitting SVM Using R

library(e1071)
dat <- data.frame(x=x, y=as.factor(y))
fit <- svm(y~., data=dat, kernel="linear", cost=10, scale=FALSE)
plot(fit,dat)

SVM with non-linear Kernel

set.seed (1)
x <- matrix(rnorm(200*2), ncol=2)
x[1:100,] <- x[1:100,]+2
x[101:150,] <- x[101:150,]-2
y <- c(rep(1,150),rep(2,50))
dat <- data.frame(x=x,y=as.factor(y))
plot(x, col=y)

SVM with non-linear Kernel

train <- sample(200,100)
fit <- svm(y~., data=dat[train,], kernel="radial", gamma=1, cost =1)
plot(fit , dat[train ,])

ROC curve

library(ROCR)
rocplot=function(pred, truth, ...){
  predob = prediction (pred, truth)
  perf = performance (predob , "tpr", "fpr")
  plot(perf ,...)}
fitted <- attributes(predict(fit, dat[train,], decision.values=TRUE))$decision.values
rocplot(fitted ,dat[train,"y"],main="Training Data")

Tuning Model Parameters

set.seed (1)
tune.out <- tune(svm, y~., data=dat[train,], kernel="radial", 
                 ranges=list(cost=c(0.1,1,10,100,1000),
                             gamma=c(0.5,1,2,3,4)))
summary(tune.out)
